				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Bero wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Having an open, honest discussion with the player base is far better approach. Yes, <span style="font-weight: bold">you will not satisfy everyone</span>. Yes, there <span style="font-weight: bold">will be flames, disagreement</span>, etc. Yes, not everyone will get what they want. But what will result are some solutions the majority of the mage community will support.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That's pretty much why they don't want "open discussion", have you seen some of the threads in our general section when they try?  It's better to have a civil, intelligent discussion with 1-5% of the player base than a 100 pages of flaming posts.
<br />

<br />
They ARE trying.  They DO want <span style="text-decoration: underline">some</span> feedback.  They have a test server and they have people they work with to help test things.  But some of these things are still a work in progress.
<br />

<br />
It's a fine line to walk.  You may hear something about incredible pet upgrades, only to have them not happen.  You may here about horrible nerfs, only to find they were a bug on Test only and fixed before it ever went live.
<br />

<br />
I didn't see the post in question, but I know how many attitudes have been lately.  The more open flaming of SoE staff, leaking private information, and "calling them out" on the message boards will just likely mean LESS information for us.
<br />

<br />
